(189, 1, '2015-10-01 12:27:42', '2015-10-01 12:27:42', 'FRC Twitter Plate\r\nUntitled design (3)\r\nThe varsity Sport for the MindTM, FRC combines the excitement of sport with the rigors of science and technology. Under strict rules, limited resources, and time limits, teams of 25 students or more are challenged to raise funds, design a team “brand,” hone teamwork skills, and build and program robots to perform prescribed tasks against a field of competitors.  It’s as close to “real-world engineering” as a student can get. Volunteer professional mentors lend their time and talents to guide each team.\r\n\r\nStudents get to:\r\n\r\ncheckbox blue  Learn from professional engineers\r\ncheckbox blue  Build and compete with a robot of their own design\r\ncheckbox blue  Learn and use sophisticated software and hardware\r\ncheckbox blue  Compete and cooperate in alliances and tournaments\r\ncheckbox blue  Earn a place in the World Championship\r\ncheckbox blue  Qualify for over $20 million in college scholarships\r\n\r\nFor information relating to the FRC Program in Australia, please click here.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n2014 Championship.\r\n\r\nxxxxxxxxxx\r\n2016 Venue Information\r\nSydney Olympic Park ~ Sports Centre\r\n\r\nFor those driving to the venue, please click here for parking information.  For directions to Sydney Olympic Park, please click here.\r\n\r\nXXXXXXX\r\n\r\nAccommodation\r\nSydney Olympic Park offers a variety of accommodation styles to suit your needs from budget to luxury options and everything in between. For teams, dormitory style accommodation is also available at the Sydney Olympic Park Lodge.\r\n\r\nAll hotels are conveniently located in the heart of Sydney Olympic Park within walking distance to venues including the Sports Centre (FRC venue) and transport.  For more information, access the hotel listing via the Sydney Olympic Park website via this link.\r\n\r\n XXXXXX\r\nPublic Transport\r\nThe Sydney Olympic Park is conveniently reached via public transport:  train and bus.  For teams flying into Sydney, the following train scheme will bring you to the Olympic Park:\r\n\r\nSTEP 1\r\nFrom: International Airport Station Platform 1, Mascot\r\nT2 Airport Line\r\nMacarthur to City via Airport or Sydenham service\r\nTo: Lidcombe Station Platform 4, Lidcombe\r\n\r\nSTEP 2\r\nFrom: Lidcombe Station Sprint Platform, Lidcombe\r\nT7 Olympic Park Line\r\nLidcombe to Olympic Park service\r\nTo: Olympic Park Station Platform 3, Sydney Olympic Park\r\n\r\n XXXXXXX\r\nFree Event\r\nThe 2016 FRC Australia Regional is a free event, open to the general public.  The opening ceremonies begin each day (Friday & Saturday, 18-19 March) at 8:30 am in the Sports Centre with matches throughout the day.  A full two-day schedule will be published soon to this site.  Visit the link below to register your attendance and let us know you are coming!\r\n\r\nClick Here for EventBrite Listing\r\n XXXXX\r\nStudents/Teachers/Principals\r\nWorkshops & Speakers TBA.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nEvent VOLUNTEERS\r\nMany volunteer positions are available for the competition.  Meals and training are provided.  If you would like to volunteer or receive information on the type of positions that need to be filled, please email Marie Efstathaniou: emarie@google.com\r\nBelow are the volunteer positions with role descriptions & days of event participation. Please note: you do not have to sign up for all three days.  Indicate which days you are available for when you contact our office.\r\n\r\nField Reset/Repair:\r\nVolunteers repair and reset the playing field after each team match. They play a critical role in ensuring smooth flow of match play and maintaining the pace of the event.\r\n\r\nPractice Day\r\nDay 1 of Competition\r\nDay 2 of Competition\r\nPractice Field Attendants: \r\nSchedule teams on the practice field. Must be organized and have the ability to maintain time schedules, and have knowledge of the game. Clean practice fields after matches. Opportunity to interact with students. These folks monitor field use to discourage teams from monopolizing the area when others are waiting to use it.\r\n\r\nPractice Day\r\nDay 1 of Competition\r\nDay 2 of Competition\r\n \r\n\r\nSafety Glasses Attendants: \r\nSafety Glasses Attendants hand out safety glasses during the event in the pit area. Ensure all teams, volunteers and spectators are wearing safety glasses at all times while in the Pits. Maintain adequate supply of safety glasses at the safety glasses locations, alert the Lead Safety Glasses Attendant when more glasses or volunteers are needed.  Maintain a high level of safety as stated in the FIRST Safety Procedures.\r\n\r\nPractice Day\r\nDay 1 of Competition\r\nDay 2 of Competition\r\n \r\n\r\nTeam Queuers: \r\nTeam Queuing volunteers are responsible for managing team traffic to and from the playing field. Team Queuers will stage and position teams in preparation for the start of matches. They play a critical role in ensuring smooth flow of match play and maintaining the pace of the event. The Lead Team Queuer will provide training during the Volunteer Orientation and Dinner.\r\n\r\nPractice Day\r\nDay 1 of Competition\r\nDay 2 of Competition', 'Seasonal Events', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '110-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-10-01 12:27:42', '2015-10-01 12:27:42', '', 110, 'http://130.56.251.93/2015/10/01/110-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
